properties.abstract: The tour Chteaux de Sion et environs is a demanding route, even for cyclists in good shape. It is also highly appealing, thanks to the variety of landscapes it passes through  including terraced vineyards, orchards and forests  plus panoramic alpine views and attractive architectural heritage (hamlets and castles).
properties.description:
The loop begins in Sion with a flat ride to Chteauneuf. Here an unsurfaced section  suitable for all tyres  plunges into nature. The trail leads under a canopy of trees along the river Morge, which rises at the Sanetsch Pass, to the vineyards and the first climb. This is dramatic, but so is the scenery: terraced vineyards and hills offering a vivid experience of the Mediterranean-style landscapes and vegetation that characterise the lower slopes of the Rhne valley.

On reaching the hamlets that make up Savise, the rewards are delightful: a flattish route, varied landscapes (hamlets, orchards, vineyards, forests) and a view across the Rhne valley to the majestic peaks beyond  such as the Dent Blanche (4,357 m) in the Val dHrens. From Grimisuat, another unsurfaced section introduces a climb along a winding and shady route. The glimpses of the floor of the Rhne valley and the fields of aromatic herbs (welcome to Ricola territory) distract from the efforts of the climb to the highest point of the itinerary: the pretty village of Arbaz, located a few kilometres from the resort of Anzre. A flat section of route offers riders a chance to get their breath back  before the superb panoramic views take it away again.

From St-Romain (starting point for the route to Rawyl and its dam/reservoir), caution is advised. The magnificent vineyards and the fine views of the floor of the Rhne valley divert attention from the route, which is narrow and steep. Its best to slow down and make photo stops. The route rejoins the valley floor at Uvrier/St-Lonard, among orchards. Here it follows the river Lienne (which rises at Rawyl) to the Rhne and its long-distance cycle trail, the Rhone Route N1 (AndermattGeneva). Closed to motorised traffic, this lane offers a fine view of the twin sentinels that are the pride of Sion: the castles of Valre and Tourbillon, dramatically perched on neighbouring crags. At their feet, Sions Old Town boasts many restaurants with sun terraces that offer an opportunity to taste the fruits of the fields, orchards and vineyards along the ride: the ultimate reward.
